## What I Did

In this lab, I first evaluated the original FLAN-T5 model on dialogue summarization examples from the DialogSum dataset.

Then I prepared the dataset by converting dialogues into instruction-style prompts and tokenizing both the model inputs and the target summaries.

The lab explored the concept of full fine-tuning, where all model parameters are updated. However, because full fine-tuning FLAN-T5-base was too expensive for my personal Google Colab environment, I implemented an educational lightweight version using FLAN-T5-small and a reduced subset of the dataset.

I also implemented a PEFT/LoRA workflow to compare parameter-efficient training with the full fine-tuning approach.
-------------------------------------------------------
## Experiments

The lab compared three model stages:

1. Original model before fine-tuning
2. Lightweight full fine-tuning workflow
3. PEFT/LoRA model

The models were evaluated qualitatively by inspecting generated summaries and quantitatively using ROUGE metrics.
-------------------------------------------------------
## Key Results

The original model produced incomplete or weak summaries in some cases.

After the lightweight fine-tuning experiment, the model behavior changed and ROUGE scores improved. The outputs were not perfect because the training setup was intentionally small, but the experiment showed that fine-tuning can influence model behavior.

The PEFT/LoRA approach trained only a small percentage of the total model parameters while still achieving measurable improvement in the educational experiment.
-------------------------------------------------------
## Key Metrics

In the lightweight experiment, ROUGE scores improved after fine-tuning.

PEFT/LoRA trained only a small percentage of the model parameters, showing how parameter-efficient methods can reduce training cost while still adapting the model to a specific task.
-------------------------------------------------------
## Key Learning

This lab showed the practical difference between full fine-tuning and parameter-efficient fine-tuning.

Full fine-tuning updates all model parameters and can be computationally expensive. PEFT/LoRA freezes most of the base model and trains only small adapter layers, making the process more efficient.

I also learned how evaluation metrics such as ROUGE can be used to compare generated summaries against human reference summaries.
-------------------------------------------------------
## Professional Takeaway

This lab helped me understand how LLMs can be adapted to specific tasks using fine-tuning and PEFT/LoRA.

It also showed how to measure improvement using both qualitative inspection and quantitative evaluation metrics.
